# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: game-physics-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] In the context of classical mechanics simulations and physics engines employed within video games, **collision response** deals with models and algorithms for simulating the changes in the motion of two solid bodies following collision and other forms of contact.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] Two rigid bodies in unconstrained motion, potentially under the action of forces, may be modelled by solving their equations of motion using numerical integration techniques.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] On collision, the kinetic properties of two such bodies seem to undergo an instantaneous change, typically resulting in the bodies rebounding away from each other, sliding, or settling into relative static contact, depending on the elasticity of the materials and the configuration of the collision.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] The origin of the rebound phenomenon, or *reaction*, may be traced to the behaviour of real bodies that, unlike their perfectly rigid idealised counterparts, do undergo minor compression on collision, followed by expansion, prior to separation.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] The compression phase converts the kinetic energy of the bodies into potential energy and to an extent, heat.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] The expansion phase converts the potential energy back to kinetic energy.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] The degree of relative kinetic energy retained after a collision, termed the *restitution*, is dependent on the elasticity of the bodies‟ materials.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] The coefficient of restitution between two given materials is modeled as the ratio $e\in [0..1]$ of the relative post-collision speed of a point of contact along the contact normal, with respect to the relative pre-collision speed of the same point along the same normal.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] These coefficients are typically determined empirically for different material pairs, such as wood against concrete or rubber against wood.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] Values for e close to zero indicate inelastic collisions such as a piece of soft clay hitting the floor, whereas values close to one represent highly elastic collisions, such as a rubber ball bouncing off a wall.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] The kinetic energy loss is relative to one body with respect to the other.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] Thus the total momentum of both bodies with respect to some common reference is unchanged after the collision, in line with the principle of *conservation of momentum*.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] Another important contact phenomenon is surface-to-surface friction, a force that impedes the relative motion of two surfaces in contact, or that of a body in a fluid.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] In this section we discuss surface-to-surface friction of two bodies in relative static contact or sliding contact.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] In the real world, friction is due to the imperfect microstructure of surfaces whose protrusions interlock into each other, generating reactive forces tangential to the surfaces.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] To overcome the friction between two bodies in static contact, the surfaces must somehow lift away from each other.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] Once in motion, the degree of surface affinity is reduced and hence bodies in sliding motion tend to offer lesser resistance to motion.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] These two categories of friction are respectively termed *static friction* and *dynamic friction*.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] It is a force which is applied to an object by another object or by a person.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] The direction of the applied force depends on how the force is applied.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] It is the support force exerted upon an object which is in contact with another stable object.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] Normal force is sometimes referred to as the pressing force since its action presses the surface together.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] Normal force is always directed towards the object and acts perpendicularly with the applied force.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] It is the force exerted by a surface as an object moves across it or makes an effort to move across it.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] The friction force opposes the motion of the object.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] Friction results when two surfaces are pressed together closely, causing attractive intermolecular forces between the molecules of the two different surface.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] As such, friction depends upon the nature of the two surfaces and upon the degree to which they are pressed together.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] Friction always acts parallel to the surface in contact and opposite the direction of motion.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] The friction force can be calculated using the equation.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] For fixed impulse $\mathbf {j}$ , the equation suggests that $t_{1}\rightarrow t_{0}\Rightarrow \left|\mathbf {f} \right|\rightarrow \infty$ , that is, a smaller time interval must be compensated by a stronger reaction force to achieve the same impulse.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] When modelling a collision between idealized rigid bodies, it is impractical to simulate the compression and expansion phases of the body geometry over the collision time interval.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] exists and is equal to $\mathbf {j}$ , the notion of *instantaneous impulses* may be introduced to simulate an instantaneous change in velocity after a collision.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] By deduction from the principle of action and reaction, if the collision impulse applied by the first body on the second body at a contact point $\mathbf {p} _{r}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ is $\mathbf {j} _{r}$ , the counter impulse applied by the second body on the first is $-\mathbf {j} _{r}$ .
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] In the subsequent formulas, $\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ is always assumed to point away from body 1 and towards body 2 at the contact point.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] where, for the i th body, $\mathbf {v} _{i}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ is the pre-collision linear velocity, $\mathbf {v'} _{i}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ is the post-collision linear velocity.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] Compute the reaction impulse vector $\mathbf {j} _{r}$ in terms of its magnitude $j_{r}$ and contact normal $\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ using $\mathbf {j} _{r}=j_{r}\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ .
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] One of the most popular models for describing friction is the Coulomb friction model.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] This model defines coefficients of static friction ${\mu }_{s}\in \mathbb {R}$ and dynamic friction ${\mu }_{d}\in \mathbb {R}$ such that ${\mu }_{s}>{\mu }_{d}$ .
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] These coefficients describe the two types of friction forces in terms of the reaction forces acting on the bodies.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] The value $f_{s}$ defines a maximum magnitude for the friction force required to counter the tangential component of any external sum force applied on a relatively static body, such that it remains static.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] Thus, if the external force is large enough, static friction is unable to fully counter this force, at which point the body gains velocity and becomes subject to dynamic friction of magnitude $f_{d}$ acting against the sliding velocity.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] The Coulomb friction model effectively defines a friction cone within which the tangential component of a force exerted by one body on the surface of another in static contact, is countered by an equal and opposite force such that the static configuration is maintained.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] Conversely, if the force falls outside the cone, static friction gives way to dynamic friction.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] where $\mathbf {f} _{e}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ is the sum of all external forces on the body.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] The multi-case definition of $\mathbf {\hat {t}}$ is required for robustly computing the actual friction force $\mathbf {f} _{f}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ for both the general and particular states of contact.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] Informally, the first case computes the tangent vector along the relative velocity component perpendicular to the contact normal $\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ .
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] If this component is zero, the second case derives $\mathbf {\hat {t}}$ in terms of the tangent component of the external force $\mathbf {f} _{e}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ .
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] If there is no tangential velocity or external forces, then no friction is assumed, and $\mathbf {\hat {t}}$ may be set to the zero vector.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] Equations (6a), (6b), (7) and (8) describe the Coulomb friction model in terms of forces.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] where $j_{r}=|\mathbf {j} _{r}|$ is the magnitude of the reaction impulse acting along contact normal $\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ .
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] Equations (5) and (10) define an impulse-based contact model that is ideal for impulse-based simulations.
[src:game-physics-engine/collision-response] When using this model, care must be taken in the choice of ${\mu }_{s}$ and ${\mu }_{d}$ as higher values may introduce additional kinetic energy into the system.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] There are two central types of physics simulations: rigid body and soft-body simulators.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] In a rigid body simulation objects are grouped into categories based on how they should interact and are less performance intensive.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] Soft-body physics involves simulating individual sections of each object such that it behaves in a more realistic way.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] A common aspect of computer games that model some type of conflict is the explosion.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] Early computer games used the simple expedient of repeating the same explosion in each circumstance.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] However, in the real world an explosion can vary depending on the terrain, altitude of the explosion, and the type of solid bodies being impacted.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] Depending on the processing power available, the effects of the explosion can be modeled as the split and shattered components propelled by the expanding gas.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] This is modelled by means of a particle system simulation.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] A particle system model allows a variety of other physical phenomena to be simulated, including smoke, moving water, precipitation, and so forth.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] The individual particles within the system are modelled using the other elements of the physics simulation rules, with the limitation that the number of particles that can be simulated is restricted by the computing power of the hardware.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] Thus explosions may need to be modelled as a small set of large particles, rather than the more accurate huge number of fine particles.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] This is a procedural animation and simulation technique to display the movement of a character when killed.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] It treats the character's body as a series of rigid bones connected together with hinges at the joints.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] The simulation models what happens to the body as it collapses to the ground.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] More sophisticated physics models of creature movement and collision interactions require greater level of computing power and a more accurate simulation of solids, liquids, and hydrodynamics.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] The modelled articulated systems can then reproduce the effects of skeleton, muscles, tendons, and other physiological components.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] Some games, such as Boneworks and Half-Life 2, apply forces to individual joints that allow ragdolls to move and behave like humanoids with fully procedural animations.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] This allows to, for example, knock an enemy down or grab each individual joint and move it around and the physics-based animation would adapt accordingly, which wouldn't be possible with conventional means.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] This method is called active ragdolls and is often used in combination with inverse kinematics.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] Projectiles, such as arrows or bullets, often travel at very high speeds.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] This creates problems with collisions - sometimes the projectile travels so fast that it simply goes past a thin object without ever detecting that it has collided with it.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] Before, this was solved with ray-casting, which does not require the creation of a physical projectile.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] However, simply shooting a ray in the direction that the weapon is aiming at is not particularly realistic, which is why modern games often create a physical projectile that can be affected by gravity and other forces.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] This projectile uses a form of continuous collision detection to make sure that the above-stated problem will not occur (at the cost of inferior performance), since more complex calculations are required to perform such a task.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] Games such as FIFA 14 require accurate projectile physics for objects such as the soccer ball.
[src:game-physics-engine/game-physics] In FIFA 14, developers were required to fix code related to the drag coefficient which was inaccurate in previous games, leading to a much more realistic simulation of a real ball.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] In 2008, Havok was honored at the 59th Annual Technology & Engineering Emmy Awards for advancing the development of physics engines in electronic entertainment.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] Telekynesis Research Limited was founded in 1998 by two university students Hugh Reynolds and Steven Collins of the computer science department in Trinity College, Dublin who would form the studio based in Dublin, Ireland.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] The software was originally named **Omniate** initially, but was then renamed to Havok (Named after the Marvel X-Men character).
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] Version 1.0 of the Havok SDK was unveiled at the Game Developers Conference (GDC) in March 2000.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] In 1999, a German-software company based in Munich had developed their own physics engine called **Ipion Virtual Physics**, it was a real-time middleware physics engine developed in the late 1990s by the German software company Ipion Software.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] Designed for the simulation of rigid body dynamics in video games and interactive media, it was a significant early competitor in the physics middleware market along with MathEngine.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] In June 2000, Ipion was acquired by Havok, and its core technologies were subsequently integrated into the **Havok Physics** engine.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] The development of the Virtual Physics engine was led by chief architect Oliver Strunk and a decentralized team of engineers across Germany.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] Developed in C++, the engine was built with cross-platform compatibility in mind, supporting Microsoft Windows, Linux, Solaris, and the PlayStation 2 console.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] On June 8, 2000, the Irish company Havok acquired Ipion.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] This merger transformed the Ipion team into Havok's Munich office, marking the company's third international location after Dublin and Palo Alto.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] The acquisition was a pivotal moment in the industry, as the sophisticated algorithms of the Ipion Virtual Physics SDK became the technological foundation for Havok's 1.5 release and beyond.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] Ipion was noted for its advanced handling of complex physical interactions for the era.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] At the time of its commercial peak, the Ipion SDK was licensed for approximately $50,000 to $60,000 per project.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] The software package provided developers with a 76-page technical manual and a comprehensive C++ library.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] Ipion's most visible legacy is found in the 3DMark 2001 SE benchmark.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] The software's "Game 4" and "Physics Feature" tests utilized the Ipion engine to demonstrate high-end hardware capabilities through complex rigid body simulations.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] It was also utilized in several retail titles, including the 2001 racing game *Route 66* (known internationally as *USA Racer*).
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] Following the Havok merger, the Ipion name was phased out, though its influence persists in modern physics simulations through its direct contribution to the Havok engine.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] It is also famously used in *Half-Life 2*, albeit heavily modified by Valve as VPhysics (VPhysics uses custom proprietary code from Valve, with additional Havok code for constraints and memory optimized partial polytype).
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] *Half-Life 2* is lauded as one of the early licensees of a real-time physics middleware such as the Ipion Virtual Physics early in its development cycle at the start of the millennium.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] The first game to utilize Havok was a game released in 1999 called London Racer developed by Davilex Games which had a long partnership with Havok/IVP.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] The Havok SDK is multi-platform by nature and is always updated to run on the majority of the latest platforms.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] Licensees are given access to most of the C/C++ source-code, giving them the freedom to customize the engine's features, or port it to different platforms although some libraries are only provided in binary format.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] In March 2011, Havok showed off a version of the Havok physics engine designed for use with the Sony Xperia Play, or more specifically, Android 2.3.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] During Microsoft's BUILD 2012 conference, Havok unveiled a full technology suite for Windows 8, Windows RT, Windows Phone 8 and later Windows 10.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] As of February 2023, Havok supports 18 targets across 10 platforms.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] These platforms include: Windows, Linux, Xbox Series S/X, PlayStation 5, iOS, Nintendo Switch and Android.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] In 2019, Unity and Havok signed a partnership to build a complete physics solution for DOTS-based projects in Unity.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] This was completed and released as production ready in December 2022.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] Havok maintains integrations for all of their products to Epic's Unreal Engine.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] Havok Physics can be used to replace the inbuilt physics engine (Chaos Physics) at an engine level, while Havok Navigation is a stand-alone plugin, and Havok Cloth is a separate tool that works alongside the engine.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] In April 2023, Babylon.js 6.0 was released with a physics implementation by Havok.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] This implementation was released as a WASM plugin and involved an overhaul of the Babylon.js Physics API.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] The first game to use Havok Physics was *London Racer* in 1999 by Davilex Games.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] In 2023, Havok products were used in twelve of the top twenty best selling video games in the United States.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] Havok supplies tools (the "Havok Content Tools") for export of assets for use with all Havok products from Autodesk 3ds Max, Autodesk Maya, and (formerly) Autodesk Softimage.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] Havok was also used in the virtual world *Second Life*, with all physics handled by its online simulator servers, rather than by the users' client computers.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] An upgrade to Havok version 4 was released in April 2008 and an upgrade to version 7 started in June 2010.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] *Second Life* resident Emilin Nakamori constructed a weight-driven, pendulum-regulated mechanical clock functioning entirely by Havok Physics in March 2019.
[src:game-physics-engine/havok-software] In 2025, Havok introduced a new pricing model targeting smaller and indie game developers, offering access to Havok Physics and Havok Navigation for a one-time, per-title fee.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] In analysis, **numerical integration** comprises a broad family of algorithms for calculating the numerical value of a definite integral.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The term **numerical quadrature** (often abbreviated to **quadrature**) is more or less a synonym for "numerical integration", especially as applied to one-dimensional integrals.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Some authors refer to numerical integration over more than one dimension as **cubature**; others take "quadrature" to include higher-dimensional integration.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] If *f*(*x*) is a smooth function integrated over a small number of dimensions, and the domain of integration is bounded, there are many methods for approximating the integral to the desired precision.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Numerical integration has roots in the geometrical problem of finding a square with the same area as a given plane figure (*quadrature* or *squaring*), as in the quadrature of the circle.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The term is also sometimes used to describe the numerical solution of differential equations.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] A formula for the integrand may be known, but it may be difficult or impossible to find an antiderivative that is an elementary function.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] An example of such an integrand is *f* (*x*) = exp(−*x*2), the antiderivative of which (the error function, times a constant) cannot be written in elementary form .
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] It may be possible to find an antiderivative symbolically, but it may be easier to compute a numerical approximation than to compute the antiderivative.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] That may be the case if the antiderivative is given as an infinite series or product, or if its evaluation requires a special function that is not available.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The term "numerical integration" first appears in 1915 in the publication *A Course in Interpolation and Numeric Integration for the Mathematical Laboratory* by David Gibb.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] "Quadrature" is a historical mathematical term that means calculating area.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Quadrature problems have served as one of the main sources of mathematical analysis.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Mathematicians of Ancient Greece, according to the Pythagorean doctrine, understood calculation of area as the process of constructing geometrically a square having the same area (*squaring*) — that is why the process was named "quadrature".
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Examples include quadrature of the circle, Lune of Hippocrates, and the treatise *Quadrature of the Parabola*.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] This construction must be performed only by means of compass and straightedge.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The ancient Babylonians used the trapezoidal rule to integrate the motion of Jupiter along the ecliptic.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] For a quadrature of a rectangle with the sides *a* and *b* it is necessary to construct a square with the side $x={\sqrt {ab}}$ (the geometric mean of *a* and *b*).
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] For this purpose it is possible to use the following fact: if we draw the circle with the sum of *a* and *b* as the diameter, then the height BH (from a point of their connection to crossing with a circle) equals their geometric mean.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The similar geometrical construction solves a problem of a quadrature for a parallelogram and a triangle.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Problems of quadrature for curvilinear figures are much more difficult.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The quadrature of the circle with compass and straightedge had been proved in the 19th century to be impossible.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Nevertheless, for some figures (for example the lune of Hippocrates) a quadrature can be performed.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The quadratures of a sphere surface and a parabola segment done by Archimedes became the highest achievement of the antique analysis.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] To prove the results, Archimedes used the method of exhaustion of Eudoxus.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] In medieval Europe the quadrature meant calculation of area by any method.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] More often the method of indivisibles was used; it was less rigorous, but more simple and powerful.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] John Wallis algebrised this method: he wrote in his *Arithmetica Infinitorum* (1656) series that we now call the definite integral, and he calculated their values.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Isaac Barrow and James Gregory made further progress: quadratures for some algebraic curves and spirals.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Christiaan Huygens successfully performed a quadrature of some solids of revolution.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The quadrature of the hyperbola by Saint-Vincent and de Sarasa provided a new function, the natural logarithm, of critical importance.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] With the invention of integral calculus came a universal method for area calculation.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] In response, the term "quadrature" has become traditional, and instead the modern phrase "*computation of a univariate definite integral*" is more common.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] A **quadrature rule** is an approximation of the definite integral of a function, usually stated as a weighted sum of function values at specified points within the domain of integration.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Numerical integration methods can generally be described as combining evaluations of the integrand to get an approximation to the integral.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The integrand is evaluated at a finite set of points called ***integration points*** and a weighted sum of these values is used to approximate the integral.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The integration points and weights depend on the specific method used and the accuracy required from the approximation.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] An important part of the analysis of any numerical integration method is to study the behavior of the approximation error as a function of the number of integrand evaluations.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] A method that yields a small error for a small number of evaluations is usually considered superior.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Reducing the number of evaluations of the integrand reduces the number of arithmetic operations involved, and therefore reduces the total error.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Also, each evaluation takes time, and the integrand may be arbitrarily complicated.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] A "brute force" kind of numerical integration can be done, if the integrand is reasonably well-behaved (i.e. piecewise continuous and of bounded variation), by evaluating the integrand with very small increments.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] This simplest method approximates the function by a step function (a piecewise constant function, or a segmented polynomial of degree zero) that passes through the point ${\textstyle \left({\frac {a+b}{2}},f\left({\frac {a+b}{2}}\right)\right)}$ .
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] A large class of quadrature rules can be derived by constructing interpolating functions that are easy to integrate.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Typically these interpolating functions are polynomials.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] In practice, since polynomials of very high degree tend to oscillate wildly, only polynomials of low degree are used, typically linear and quadratic.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The interpolating function may be a straight line (an affine function, i.e. a polynomial of degree 1) passing through the points $\left(a,f(a)\right)$ and $\left(b,f(b)\right)$ .
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] For either one of these rules, we can make a more accurate approximation by breaking up the interval $[a,b]$ into some number n of subintervals, computing an approximation for each subinterval, then adding up all the results.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] This is called a *composite rule*, *extended rule*, or *iterated rule*.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] where the subintervals have the form $[a+kh,a+(k+1)h]\subset [a,b],$ with ${\textstyle h={\frac {b-a}{n}}}$ and $k=0,\ldots ,n-1.$ Here we used subintervals of the same length h but one could also use intervals of varying length $\left(h_{k}\right)_{k}$ .
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Interpolation with polynomials evaluated at equally spaced points in $[a,b]$ yields the Newton–Cotes formulas, of which the rectangle rule and the trapezoidal rule are examples.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Simpson's rule, which is based on a polynomial of order 2, is also a Newton–Cotes formula.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Quadrature rules with equally spaced points have the very convenient property of *nesting*.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The corresponding rule with each interval subdivided includes all the current points, so those integrand values can be re-used.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] If we allow the intervals between interpolation points to vary, we find another group of quadrature formulas, such as the Gaussian quadrature formulas.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] A Gaussian quadrature rule is typically more accurate than a Newton–Cotes rule that uses the same number of function evaluations, if the integrand is smooth (i.e., if it is sufficiently differentiable).
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Other quadrature methods with varying intervals include Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature (also called Fejér quadrature) methods, which do nest.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Gaussian quadrature rules do not nest, but the related Gauss–Kronrod quadrature formulas do.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Adaptive quadrature is a numerical integration method in which the integral of a function $f(x)$ is approximated using static quadrature rules on adaptively refined subintervals of the region of integration.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Generally, adaptive algorithms are just as efficient and effective as traditional algorithms for "well behaved" integrands, but are also effective for "badly behaved" integrands for which traditional algorithms may fail.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The accuracy of a quadrature rule of the Newton–Cotes type is generally a function of the number of evaluation points.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The result is usually more accurate as the number of evaluation points increases, or, equivalently, as the width of the step size between the points decreases.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] It is natural to ask what the result would be if the step size were allowed to approach zero.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] This can be answered by extrapolating the result from two or more nonzero step sizes, using series acceleration methods such as Richardson extrapolation.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The extrapolation function may be a polynomial or rational function.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Extrapolation methods are described in more detail by Stoer and Bulirsch (Section 3.4) and are implemented in many of the routines in the QUADPACK library.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] where the supremum was used to approximate.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Hence, if we approximate the integral ${\textstyle \int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx}$ by the quadrature rule $(b-a)f(a)$ our error is no greater than the right hand side of **1**.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] We can convert this into an error analysis for the Riemann sum, giving an upper bound of ${\frac {n^{-1}}{2}}\sup _{0\leq x\leq 1}\left|f'(x)\right|$ for the error term of that particular approximation.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] (Note that this is precisely the error we calculated for the example $f(x)=x$ .) Using more derivatives, and by tweaking the quadrature, we can do a similar error analysis using a Taylor series (using a partial sum with remainder term) for *f*.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] This error analysis gives a strict upper bound on the error, if the derivatives of *f* are available.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] This integration method can be combined with interval arithmetic to produce computer proofs and *verified* calculations.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Several methods exist for approximate integration over unbounded intervals.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The standard technique involves specially derived quadrature rules, such as Gauss-Hermite quadrature for integrals on the whole real line and Gauss-Laguerre quadrature for integrals on the positive reals.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The quadrature rules discussed so far are all designed to compute one-dimensional integrals.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] To compute integrals in multiple dimensions, one approach is to phrase the multiple integral as repeated one-dimensional integrals by applying Fubini's theorem (the tensor product rule).
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] This approach requires the function evaluations to grow exponentially as the number of dimensions increases.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Three methods are known to overcome this so-called *curse of dimensionality*.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] A great many additional techniques for forming multidimensional cubature integration rules for a variety of weighting functions are given in the monograph by Stroud.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Integration on the sphere has been reviewed by Hesse et al.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Monte Carlo methods and quasi-Monte Carlo methods are easy to apply to multi-dimensional integrals.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] They may yield greater accuracy for the same number of function evaluations than repeated integrations using one-dimensional methods.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] A large class of useful Monte Carlo methods are the so-called Markov chain Monte Carlo algorithms, which include the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm and Gibbs sampling.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Sparse grids were originally developed by Smolyak for the quadrature of high-dimensional functions.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The method is always based on a one-dimensional quadrature rule, but performs a more sophisticated combination of univariate results.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] However, whereas the tensor product rule guarantees that the weights of all of the cubature points will be positive if the weights of the quadrature points were positive, Smolyak's rule does not guarantee that the weights will all be positive.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Bayesian quadrature is a statistical approach to the numerical problem of computing integrals and falls under the field of probabilistic numerics.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] It can provide a full handling of the uncertainty over the solution of the integral expressed as a Gaussian process posterior variance.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] can be reduced to an initial value problem for an ordinary differential equation by applying the first part of the fundamental theorem of calculus.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Numerical methods for ordinary differential equations, such as Runge–Kutta methods, can be applied to the restated problem and thus be used to evaluate the integral.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] For instance, the standard fourth-order Runge–Kutta method applied to the differential equation yields Simpson's rule from above.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The differential equation $F'(x)=f(x)$ has a special form: the right-hand side contains only the independent variable (here x ) and not the dependent variable (here F ).
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] This simplifies the theory and algorithms considerably.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] The problem of evaluating integrals is thus best studied in its own right.
[src:game-physics-engine/numerical-integration] Conversely, the term "quadrature" may also be used for the solution of differential equations: "solving by quadrature" or "reduction to quadrature" means expressing its solution in terms of integrals.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] A **physics engine** is computer software that provides an approximate simulation of certain physical systems, typically classical dynamics, including rigid body dynamics (including collision detection), soft body dynamics, and fluid dynamics.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] It is of use in the domains of computer graphics, video games and film (CGI).
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Their main uses are in video games (typically as middleware), in which case the simulations are in real-time.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] The term is sometimes used more generally to describe any software system for simulating physical phenomena, such as high-performance scientific simulation.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] There are generally two classes of physics engines: real-time and high-precision.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] High-precision physics engines require more processing power to calculate very precise physics and are usually used by scientists and prerendered computer animation, such as movies.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Real-time physics engines—as used in video games and other forms of interactive computing—use simplified calculations and decreased accuracy to compute in time for the game to respond at an appropriate rate for game play.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] A physics engine is essentially a big calculator that does mathematics needed to simulate physics.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] One of the first general purpose computers, ENIAC, was used as a very simple type of physics engine.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] It was used to design ballistics tables to help the United States military estimate where artillery shells of various mass would land when fired at varying angles and gunpowder charges, also accounting for drift caused by wind.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] The results were calculated a single time only, and were tabulated into printed tables handed out to the artillery commanders.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Physics engines have been commonly used on supercomputers since the 1980s to perform computational fluid dynamics modeling, where particles are assigned force vectors that are combined to show circulation.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Due to the requirements of speed and high precision, special computer processors known as vector processors were developed to accelerate the calculations.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] The techniques can be used to model weather patterns in weather forecasting, wind tunnel data for designing air- and watercraft or motor vehicles including racecars, and thermal cooling of computer processors for improving heat sinks.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] As with many calculation-laden processes in computing, the accuracy of the simulation is related to the resolution of the simulation and the precision of the calculations; small fluctuations not modeled in the simulation can drastically change the predicted results.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Tire manufacturers use physics simulations to examine how new tire tread types will perform under wet and dry conditions, using new tire materials of varying flexibility and under different levels of weight loading.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] The simulations optimize tire operations, material selection, costs, and enhance time efficiency.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] In most computer games, speed of the processors and gameplay are more important than accuracy of simulation.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] This leads to designs for physics engines that produce results in real-time but that replicate real world physics only for simple cases and typically with some approximation.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] More often than not, the simulation is geared towards providing a "perceptually correct" approximation rather than a real simulation.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] However some game engines, such as Source, use physics in puzzles or in combat situations.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] This requires more accurate physics so that, for example, the momentum of an object can knock over an obstacle or lift a sinking object.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Physically-based character animation in the past only used rigid body dynamics because they are faster and easier to calculate, but modern games and movies are starting to use soft body physics.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Soft body physics are also used for particle effects, liquids and cloth.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Some form of limited fluid dynamics simulation is sometimes provided to simulate water and other liquids as well as the flow of fire and explosions through the air.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Objects in games interact with the player, the environment, and each other.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Typically, most 3D objects in games are represented by two separate meshes or shapes.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] One of these meshes is the highly complex and detailed shape visible to the player in the game, such as a vase with elegant curved and looping handles.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] For purpose of speed, a second, simplified invisible mesh is used to represent the object to the physics engine so that the physics engine treats the example vase as a simple cylinder.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] It would thus be impossible to insert a rod or fire a projectile through the handle holes on the vase, because the physics engine model is based on the cylinder and is unaware of the handles.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] The simplified mesh used for physics processing is often referred to as the collision geometry.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] This may be a bounding box, sphere, or convex hull.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Engines that use bounding boxes or bounding spheres as the final shape for collision detection are considered extremely simple.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Generally a bounding box is used for broad phase collision detection to narrow down the number of possible collisions before costly mesh on mesh collision detection is done in the narrow phase of collision detection.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Another aspect of precision in discrete collision detection involves the framerate, or the number of moments in time per second when physics is calculated.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Each frame is treated as separate from all other frames, and the space between frames is not calculated.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] A low framerate and a small fast-moving object causes a situation where the object does not move smoothly through space but instead seems to teleport from one point in space to the next as each frame is calculated.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Projectiles moving at sufficiently high speeds will miss targets, if the target is small enough to fit in the gap between the calculated frames of the fast moving projectile.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Various techniques are used to overcome this flaw, such as *Second Life*'s representation of projectiles as arrows with invisible trailing tails longer than the gap in frames to collide with any object that might fit between the calculated frames.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] By contrast, continuous collision detection such as in Bullet or Havok does not suffer this problem.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] An alternative to using bounding box-based rigid body physics systems is to use a finite element-based system.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] In such a system, a 3-dimensional, volumetric tessellation is created of the 3D object.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] The tessellation results in a number of finite elements which represent aspects of the object's physical properties such as toughness, plasticity, and volume preservation.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Once constructed, the finite elements are used by a solver to model the stress within the 3D object.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] The stress can be used to drive fracture, deformation and other physical effects with a high degree of realism and uniqueness.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] As the number of modeled elements is increased, the engine's ability to model physical behavior increases.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] The visual representation of the 3D object is altered by the finite element system through the use of a deformation shader run on the CPU or GPU.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Finite Element-based systems had been impractical for use in games due to the performance overhead and the lack of tools to create finite element representations out of 3D art objects.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] James O'Brien as a part of his PhD thesis.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] In the real world, physics is always active.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] There is a constant Brownian motion jitter to all particles in our universe as the forces push back and forth against each other.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] For a game physics engine, such constant active precision is unnecessarily wasting the limited CPU power, which can cause problems such as decreased framerate.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Thus, games may put objects to "sleep" by disabling the computation of physics on objects that have not moved a particular distance within a certain amount of time.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] For example, in the 3D virtual world Second Life, if an object is resting on the floor and the object does not move beyond a minimal distance in about two seconds, then the physics calculations are disabled for the object and it becomes frozen in place.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] The object remains frozen until physics processing reactivates for the object after collision occurs with some other active physical object.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Physics engines for video games typically have two core components, a collision detection/collision response system, and the dynamics simulation component responsible for solving the forces affecting the simulated objects.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Modern physics engines may also contain fluid simulations, animation control systems and asset integration tools.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Finally, hybrid methods are possible that combine aspects of the above paradigms.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] A primary limit of physics engine realism is the approximated result of the constraint resolutions and collision result due to the slow convergence of algorithms.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Collision detection computed at a too low frequency can result in objects passing through each other and then being repelled with an abnormal correction force.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] On the other hand, approximated results of reaction force is due to the slow convergence of typical Projected Gauss Seidel solver resulting in abnormal bouncing.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Any type of free-moving compound physics object can demonstrate this problem, but it is especially prone to affecting chain links under high tension, and wheeled objects with actively physical bearing surfaces.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Higher precision reduces the positional/force errors, but at the cost of needing greater CPU power for the calculations.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] A physics processing unit (PPU) is a dedicated microprocessor designed to handle the calculations of physics, especially in the physics engine of video games.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Examples of calculations involving a PPU might include rigid body dynamics, soft body dynamics, collision detection, fluid dynamics, hair and clothing simulation, finite element analysis, and fracturing of objects.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] The idea is that specialized processors offload time-consuming tasks from a computer's CPU, much like how a GPU performs graphics operations in the main CPU's place.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] The term was coined by Ageia's marketing to describe their PhysX chip to consumers.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Several other technologies in the CPU-GPU spectrum have some features in common with it, although Ageia's solution was the only complete one designed, marketed, supported, and placed within a system *exclusively* as a PPU.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] Hardware acceleration for physics processing is now usually provided by graphics processing units that support more general computation, a concept known as general-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU).
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] AMD and NVIDIA provide support for rigid body dynamics computations on their latest graphics cards.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] NVIDIA's GeForce 8 series supports a GPU-based Newtonian physics acceleration technology named *Quantum Effects Technology*.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] NVIDIA provides an SDK Toolkit for CUDA (Compute Unified Device Architecture) technology that offers both a low and high-level API to the GPU.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] For their GPUs, AMD offers a similar SDK, called Close to Metal (CTM), which provides a thin hardware interface.
[src:game-physics-engine/physics-engine] PhysX is an example of a physics engine that can use GPGPU based hardware acceleration when it is available.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] In classical mechanics, **rigid body dynamics** studies the movement of systems of interconnected bodies under the action of external forces.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Along with statics, it forms the field of **rigid body mechanics**.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The assumption that the bodies are *rigid* (i.e. they do not deform under the action of applied forces) simplifies analysis, by reducing the parameters that describe the configuration of the system to the translation and rotation of body-fixed frames.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] This excludes bodies that display fluid, highly elastic, and plastic behavior.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The dynamics of a rigid body system is described by the laws of kinematics and by the application of Newton's second law (kinetics) or their derivative form, Lagrangian mechanics.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The solution of these equations of motion provides a description of the position, the motion and the acceleration of the individual components of the system, and overall the system itself, as a function of time.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The formulation and solution of rigid body dynamics is an important tool in the computer simulation of mechanical systems.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] If a system of particles moves parallel to a fixed plane, the system is said to be constrained to planar movement.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] In this case, Newton's laws (kinetics) for a rigid system of N particles, P*i*, *i*=1,...,*N*, simplify because there is no movement in the *k* direction.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] where **r**i denotes the planar trajectory of each particle.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] For systems that are constrained to planar movement, the angular velocity and angular acceleration vectors are directed along **k** perpendicular to the plane of movement, which simplifies this acceleration equation.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] where ${\textstyle \mathbf {e} _{i}\times \mathbf {e} _{i}=0}$ and ${\textstyle \mathbf {e} _{i}\times \mathbf {t} _{i}=\mathbf {k} }$ is the unit vector perpendicular to the plane for all of the particles Pi.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] where M is the total mass and *I***C** is the moment of inertia about an axis perpendicular to the movement of the rigid system and through the center of mass.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Several methods to describe orientations of a rigid body in three dimensions have been developed.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] They are summarized in the following sections.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The first attempt to represent an orientation is attributed to Leonhard Euler.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The values of these three rotations are called Euler angles.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Commonly, $\psi$ is used to denote precession, $\theta$ nutation, and $\phi$ intrinsic rotation.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] These are three angles, also known as yaw, pitch and roll, Navigation angles and Cardan angles.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Mathematically they constitute a set of six possibilities inside the twelve possible sets of Euler angles, the ordering being the one best used for describing the orientation of a vehicle such as an airplane.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] In aerospace engineering they are usually referred to as Euler angles.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Euler also realized that the composition of two rotations is equivalent to a single rotation about a different fixed axis (Euler's rotation theorem).
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, the composition of the former three angles has to be equal to only one rotation, whose axis was complicated to calculate until matrices were developed.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Based on this fact he introduced a vectorial way to describe any rotation, with a vector on the rotation axis and module equal to the value of the angle.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, any orientation can be represented by a rotation vector (also called Euler vector) that leads to it from the reference frame.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent an orientation, the rotation vector is commonly called orientation vector, or attitude vector.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] A similar method, called axis-angle representation, describes a rotation or orientation using a unit vector aligned with the rotation axis, and a separate value to indicate the angle (see figure).
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] With the introduction of matrices the Euler theorems were rewritten.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The rotations were described by orthogonal matrices referred to as rotation matrices or direction cosine matrices.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent an orientation, a rotation matrix is commonly called orientation matrix, or attitude matrix.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The above-mentioned Euler vector is the eigenvector of a rotation matrix (a rotation matrix has a unique real eigenvalue).
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The product of two rotation matrices is the composition of rotations.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, as before, the orientation can be given as the rotation from the initial frame to achieve the frame that we want to describe.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The configuration space of a non-symmetrical object in *n*-dimensional space is SO(*n*) × **R***n*.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Orientation may be visualized by attaching a basis of tangent vectors to an object.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The direction in which each vector points determines its orientation.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Another way to describe rotations is using rotation quaternions, also called versors.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] They are equivalent to rotation matrices and rotation vectors.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] With respect to rotation vectors, they can be more easily converted to and from matrices.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent orientations, rotation quaternions are typically called orientation quaternions or attitude quaternions.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] To consider rigid body dynamics in three-dimensional space, Newton's second law must be extended to define the relationship between the movement of a rigid body and the system of forces and torques that act on it.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The extension of Newton's second law to rigid bodies is achieved by considering a rigid system of particles.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] If a system of *N* particles, Pi, i=1,...,*N*, are assembled into a rigid body, then Newton's second law can be applied to each of the particles in the body.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] An important simplification to these force equations is obtained by introducing the resultant force and torque that acts on the rigid system.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] This resultant force and torque is obtained by choosing one of the particles in the system as a reference point, **R**, where each of the external forces are applied with the addition of an associated torque.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The resultant force **F** and torque **T** are given by the formulas, $\mathbf {F} =\sum _{i=1}^{N}\mathbf {F} _{i},\quad \mathbf {T} =\sum _{i=1}^{N}(\mathbf {R} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )\times \mathbf {F} _{i},$ where **R**i is the vector that defines the position of particle Pi.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The mass properties of the rigid body are represented by its center of mass and inertia matrix.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] then it is known as the center of mass of the system.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] where $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ is the column vector **R**i − **R**; $\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}$ is its transpose, and $\mathbf {I}$ is the 3 by 3 identity matrix.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] $\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}\mathbf {S} _{i}$ is the scalar product of $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ with itself, while $\mathbf {S} _{i}\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}$ is the tensor product of $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ with itself.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Using the center of mass and inertia matrix, the force and torque equations for a single rigid body take the form $\mathbf {F} =m\mathbf {a} ,\quad \mathbf {T} =[I_{R}]\alpha +\omega \times [I_{R}]\omega ,$ and are known as Newton's second law of motion for a rigid body.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The dynamics of an interconnected system of rigid bodies, *B**i*, *j* = 1, ..., *M*, is formulated by isolating each rigid body and introducing the interaction forces.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Newton's formulation yields 6*M* equations that define the dynamics of a system of *M* rigid bodies.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] A rotating object, whether under the influence of torques or not, may exhibit the behaviours of precession and nutation.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The solution to this equation when there is no applied torque is discussed in the articles Euler's equation of motion and Poinsot's ellipsoid.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] It follows from Euler's equation that a torque **τ** applied perpendicular to the axis of rotation, and therefore perpendicular to **L**, results in a rotation about an axis perpendicular to both **τ** and **L**.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Precession can be demonstrated by placing a spinning top with its axis horizontal and supported loosely (frictionless toward precession) at one end.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Instead of falling, as might be expected, the top appears to defy gravity by remaining with its axis horizontal, when the other end of the axis is left unsupported and the free end of the axis slowly describes a circle in a horizontal plane, the resulting precession turning.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] This effect is explained by the above equations.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The torque on the top is supplied by a couple of forces: gravity acting downward on the device's centre of mass, and an equal force acting upward to support one end of the device.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Under a constant torque of magnitude *τ*, the speed of precession *Ω*P is inversely proportional to *L*, the magnitude of its angular momentum: $\tau ={\mathit {\Omega }}_{\mathrm {P} }L\sin \theta ,$ where *θ* is the angle between the vectors **Ω**P and **L**.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Thus, if the top's spin slows down (for example, due to friction), its angular momentum decreases and so the rate of precession increases.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] This continues until the device is unable to rotate fast enough to support its own weight, when it stops precessing and falls off its support, mostly because friction against precession cause another precession that goes to cause the fall.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] By convention, these three vectors – torque, spin, and precession – are all oriented with respect to each other according to the right-hand rule.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] An alternate formulation of rigid body dynamics that has a number of convenient features is obtained by considering the virtual work of forces acting on a rigid body.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The virtual work of forces acting at various points on a single rigid body can be calculated using the velocities of their point of application and the resultant force and torque.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The trajectories of **R***i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n* are defined by the movement of the rigid body.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The velocity of the points **R***i* along their trajectories are $\mathbf {V} _{i}={\boldsymbol {\omega }}\times (\mathbf {R} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {V} ,$ where **ω** is the angular velocity vector of the body.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] is known as the generalized force associated with the virtual displacement δq.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] It is useful to note that conservative forces such as gravity and spring forces are derivable from a potential function *V*(*q*1, ..., *q**n*), known as a potential energy.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The equations of motion for a mechanical system of rigid bodies can be determined using D'Alembert's form of the principle of virtual work.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The principle of virtual work is used to study the static equilibrium of a system of rigid bodies; however, by introducing acceleration terms in Newton's laws this approach is generalized to define dynamic equilibrium.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The static equilibrium of a mechanical system rigid bodies is defined by the condition that the virtual work of the applied forces is zero for any virtual displacement of the system.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] This is known as the *principle of virtual work.* This is equivalent to the requirement that the generalized forces for any virtual displacement are zero, that is *Q**i*=0.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Let a mechanical system be constructed from n rigid bodies, B*i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*, and let the resultant of the applied forces on each body be the force-torque pairs, **F***i* and **T***i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Notice that these applied forces do not include the reaction forces where the bodies are connected.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Finally, assume that the velocity **V***i* and angular velocities ***ω****i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*, for each rigid body, are defined by a single generalized coordinate q.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Such a system of rigid bodies is said to have one degree of freedom.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] These m equations define the static equilibrium of the system of rigid bodies.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Consider a single rigid body which moves under the action of a resultant force **F** and torque **T**, with one degree of freedom defined by the generalized coordinate *q*.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] D'Alembert's form of the principle of virtual work states that a system of rigid bodies is in dynamic equilibrium when the virtual work of the sum of the applied forces and the inertial forces is zero for any virtual displacement of the system.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Thus, dynamic equilibrium of a system of n rigid bodies with m generalized coordinates requires that $\delta W=\left(Q_{1}+Q_{1}^{*}\right)\delta q_{1}+\dots +\left(Q_{m}+Q_{m}^{*}\right)\delta q_{m}=0,$ for any set of virtual displacements *δq**j*.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] In this case, introduce the Lagrangian, *L* = *T* − *V*, so these equations of motion become ${\frac {d}{dt}}{\frac {\partial L}{\partial {\dot {q}}_{j}}}-{\frac {\partial L}{\partial q_{j}}}=0\quad j=1,\ldots ,m.$ These are known as Lagrange's equations of motion.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] The linear and angular momentum of a rigid system of particles is formulated by measuring the position and velocity of the particles relative to the center of mass.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Let the system of particles Pi, *i* = 1, ..., *n* be located at the coordinates **r***i* and velocities **v***i*.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] To specialize these formulas to a rigid body, assume the particles are rigidly connected to each other so Pi, i=1,...,n are located by the coordinates **r**i and velocities **v**i.
[src:game-physics-engine/rigid-body-dynamics] Select a reference point **R** and compute the relative position and velocity vectors, $\mathbf {r} _{i}=(\mathbf {r} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {R} ,\quad \mathbf {v} _{i}=\omega \times (\mathbf {r} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {V} ,$ where ω is the angular velocity of the system.
